 Sorry about that.

56
00:14:21,980 --> 00:14:29,980
 Okay, my name is Greg Sund. I've been involved in local government since 1983.

57
00:14:29,980 --> 00:14:37,980
 I first became involved in local government by running for office in Deadwood, South Dakota.

58
00:14:37,980 --> 00:14:53,980
 And that really engaged me in local government. And eventually I went back to school and got my master's in public administration and started full time in this field at the beginning of 1992.

59
00:14:53,980 --> 00:15:06,980
 Since that time I've served cities and a county in South Dakota, North Dakota, Kansas, and starting in 2017 Colorado.

60
00:15:06,980 --> 00:15:22,980
 I served as the city administrator, excuse me, city manager in Trinidad, Colorado, where I live right now from 2017 through the most of 2019.

61
00:15:22,980 --> 00:15:37,980
 I have been serving in interim positions since 2020. Those include Walsenberg, Telluride, Mount Crested Butte, George and Georgetown.

62
00:15:37,980 --> 00:15:51,980
 I have had the luck of being involved in some really interesting projects throughout my career. I think the one that I will always highlight and feel very honored to have been involved in.

63
00:15:51,980 --> 00:15:57,980
 Was the purchase of what's called the crazy French ranch south of Trinidad.

64
00:15:57,980 --> 00:16:04,980
 It eventually became the 42nd state park in this little Fisher's Peak State Park.

65
00:16:04,980 --> 00:16:09,980
 It was the purchase of a 19,200 acre ranch.

66
00:16:09,980 --> 00:16:26,980
 And even though the city was involved in the process, we were mostly the cheerleaders and getting the people who are local who are interested in the project, getting them and keeping them involved and up to communication of what we were doing.

67
00:16:26,980 --> 00:16:41,980
 Most of the project was negotiated by the Trust for Public Land and the nature conservancy. Those people were very involved in the project and negotiated with the owner and the purchase of the property.

68
00:16:41,980 --> 00:16:56,980
 And we also worked with GOCO and with Gamefish and Parks because they were all GOCO and Gamefish and Parks provided all of the financing for that project.

69
00:16:56,980 --> 00:17:20,980
 I use Fisher's Peak State Park on a regular basis. I have an active mountain biker, and enjoy riding up the amount of the mountain I can get up with some of it is too steep to ride, but it's interesting to be able to do that and have it so close to my place of residence.

70
00:17:20,980 --> 00:17:23,980
 Are there any questions for me.

71
00:17:23,980 --> 00:17:28,980
 Yeah, I'm going to open it up to the trustees to ask some questions.

72
00:17:28,980 --> 00:17:33,980
 Everybody and just go ahead and go ahead.

73
00:17:33,980 --> 00:17:35,980
 You want to go back to the question.

74
00:17:35,980 --> 00:17:45,980
 Thank you very much for being here. We really appreciate you taking the time to read our.

75
00:17:45,980 --> 00:17:52,980
 Read about our needs and step up like this. Thank you.

76
00:17:52,980 --> 00:18:00,980
 What is it that you like about being an interim manager or town administrator.

77
00:18:00,980 --> 00:18:06,980
 And it seems like that's kind of the direction you shifted towards.

78
00:18:06,980 --> 00:18:23,980
 I decided after Trinidad that I just wasn't in the mood to move out anymore. I just wanted to stay in one location. And the best way to do that for me is to serve an interim positions that have a start to stop date, and then I can return home.

79
00:18:23,980 --> 00:18:42,980
 This is a field where if you actively pursue positions, you move all the time. And I've done that numerous times in my career, and I just didn't feel like doing it anymore, which is why I got into the interim positions.

80
00:18:42,980 --> 00:18:53,980
 And when you come in as an interim, you know, it's a very tumultuous time to begin with, and any municipality or government.

81
00:18:53,980 --> 00:19:17,980
 How do you feel about your role in helping staff and board and mayors, and most importantly, the public, the people or community transition from a town administrator to an interim to a new town administrator.

82
00:19:17,980 --> 00:19:30,980
 I think that is a big part of the role is to prepare people for incoming of another administrator in the near future, but also to provide continuity in the management of the community.

83
00:19:30,980 --> 00:19:41,980
 Because when you go without someone for a while, then you lose that continuity and the new person really has to start at square one and start building it all over again.

84
00:19:41,980 --> 00:20:00,980
 And sometimes that takes an entirely different view. There's people that don't know the history and start out in a direction they think is appropriate to maybe it's not one that the town wants to go in, and they have to learn that along the way rather than having

85
00:20:00,980 --> 00:20:19,980
 the continuity that already exists. Also, when there's projects that are on the table that continuity is really important in keeping those moving forward, finishing them when possible, and not just leaving everything on the plate for the new administrator that's hired.

86
00:20:19,980 --> 00:20:37,980
 So, continuing to say our grant projects, our water projects, our infrastructure, and making sure that we are still meeting all of our grant requirements, and keeping up on that that is something that you are comfortable going and have experience to it.

87
00:20:37,980 --> 00:20:55,980
 Yes. Now, I'll say that these grant programs change all the time so the ones that you have, I'm going to have to come up with speed on but I have managed grants in the past and it's the process that tends to be fairly involved, especially on federal grants.

88
00:20:55,980 --> 00:21:08,980
 But it's not something that's the owners can't do, you just have to keep that up and not let any time lapse and fail to do the reporting that's necessary.

89
00:21:08,980 --> 00:21:10,980
 Thank you.

90
00:21:10,980 --> 00:21:18,980
 What is the smallest town. I mean, it's a penalty that you have managed.

91
00:21:18,980 --> 00:21:29,980
 Probably Mount Crested Butte. It was about 900 population. Okay, so you do have experience with a smaller population.

92
00:21:29,980 --> 00:21:40,980
 It is very different indeed. My first, my first full time position was in Platte, South Dakota. It was a town of 1300 people.

93
00:21:40,980 --> 00:21:50,980
 And at the time, South Dakota really didn't have very many administrators or managers, it was a fairly rare form of government in 92.

94
00:21:50,980 --> 00:21:59,980
 And so I served as the city finance officer, which also had a lot of the responsibilities of the administrator.

95
00:21:59,980 --> 00:22:02,980
 Thank you.

96
00:22:02,980 --> 00:22:16,980
 Hi, this is Walter check speaking. I, to read touched on what I think is one of our major concern, and that is the grant funded.

97
00:22:16,980 --> 00:22:31,980
 Infrastructure projects were in the middle of right now. And I'm all, you kind of answered the question, but I sort of like to hear a little more about your comfort level of just taking over the grant project.

98
00:22:31,980 --> 00:22:50,980
 A grant project that is already started, and in the process of, as a matter of fact, we just sent out some RFP for the next phase of a major water project, as well as some other infrastructure projects that we have going on.

99
00:22:50,980 --> 00:23:01,980
 And like you said, those are the things we don't want to let lapse, and they need continually monitoring and reporting on.

100
00:23:01,980 --> 00:23:04,980
 So I was just curious.

101
00:23:04,980 --> 00:23:26,980
 I have the advantage of being able to start the position fairly soon and be able to spend a little time with your current administrator to get background on what the projects are, how they're functioning, how the reporting is going, how the project itself is advancing,

102
00:23:26,980 --> 00:23:43,980
 or if there's any problems in getting that done at this time, because the more issues that you can resolve and move forward from the easier it is to finish a project.

103
00:23:43,980 --> 00:23:59,980
 Okay, I'll just. So, first of all, thank you very much for being here on such short notice, and some of the things that we said we talked about before we were able to get this meeting set up is, is again the projects we have.

104
00:23:59,980 --> 00:24:17,980
 One of the things that really intrigued me about the resume is that you were a public works director, I don't quite remember where, but you, you sounds like quite a bit of experience with public works, and we need to hire a new public works director so I'm very happy to potentially have your input into that.

105
00:24:17,980 --> 00:24:36,980
 Oh, well, and I'm in the office a lot more so than a trustee would be, and I see how important it is to have a person in the office that has not only information on the day to day activities and the things that come up that are expected and unexpected but also

106
00:24:36,980 --> 00:24:53,980
 the overall view that the administrator has to do is the chief operating officer actually, and how important that person is, and for the staff's well being and the staff's continuity and their confidence that they have someone they can turn to when they're when things come up in their

107
00:24:53,980 --> 00:25:05,980
 community, that they're not used to because I see that all the time, but I'm in the office just just being nearest mayor, so I'm quite impressed with your background on that and appreciative that you can be here full time.

108
00:25:05,980 --> 00:25:14,980
 We had a previous administrator was very helpful but she was part time and at that time we didn't have any projects like this going on we now have.

109
00:25:14,980 --> 00:25:36,980
 Well, we just finished one project which was we had to rely on our water tank and I believe we are soon to be getting water from that realign to money gallon tank, but we have the next project that trusty check was referring to is we're replacing 10,000 feet of transmission line from our 2 million gallon tank to most of our users.

110
00:25:36,980 --> 00:25:54,980
 That's the RFP that's out and I don't know when that closes but I know it's soon that the proposal should be coming in soon for that I'm looking out at public works, but your timing could be that you would also be available to renew those, because this is going to be so important

111
00:25:54,980 --> 00:26:06,980
 and a good contractor doing this very it's going to be very visible and very intensive work just outside of town and lots of people drive this way.

112
00:26:06,980 --> 00:26:22,980
 It's going to be a huge project lots of equipment, a lot of safety issues that really needs a good management oversight from 30,000 foot level so in my discussions with you and your resume it seems like you have that kind of experience.

113
00:26:22,980 --> 00:26:26,980
 Do you agree with me or am I, am I embellishing you too much.

114
00:26:26,980 --> 00:26:40,980
 I had the opportunity to serve as a public works director for Hayes Kansas for two years, but in the administrative and manager roles I've had, I've had to work with public works directors throughout my career.

115
00:26:40,980 --> 00:26:57,980
 And whether that was with people who had the title of public works director or whether it was split between two or more people, it's still work that has to be done. I have been involved in water issues and interest in water issues for as long as I can

116
00:26:57,980 --> 00:27:18,980
 remember at one time I had a class two or I think that's class C licensed equivalent in Colorado for wastewater treatment. I operate a wastewater treatment for the home state gold mine and lead soft Dakota.

117
00:27:18,980 --> 00:27:32,980
 So even though that was an industrial operation, it is you had to learn all of the basics of wastewater treatment in order to get the classifications necessary to perform the position.

118
00:27:32,980 --> 00:27:52,980
 When I was in Dickinson, North Dakota, we had very active involvement in upgrading our water and sewer infrastructure on a regular basis, and we're doing a good job of getting that done. I think I'm a big believer that when you can you should dedicate as much money as possible

119
00:27:52,980 --> 00:28:10,980
 to ongoing upgrading and maintenance of those facilities because they're underground, it's easy to forget them. And a lot of cities do it. And when those kind of lines go bad, they go bad all at once a lot of times.

120
00:28:10,980 --> 00:28:31,980
 I also can affirm believer that when a line breaks rather than just fixing that break, you should do what you can to replace as much line as possible around it, because if there's a break in one part of a piece of pipe, chances are there's other pieces of that pipe that are all slow in danger.

121
00:28:31,980 --> 00:28:35,980
 And you might end up having multiple breaks rather than one.

122
00:28:35,980 --> 00:28:39,980
 If you try to do it as little work as possible.

123
00:28:39,980 --> 00:28:45,980
 Yep, we have met. There's been a lot of postponement to getting this work done. And now.

124
00:28:45,980 --> 00:29:04,980
 And again, as everybody in this room knows, in Colorado, it's an enterprise. So we've been very fortunate through our previous current and administrator of getting the grants and loans that we have. Otherwise, the water use with their bills would be exorbitant to try to pay for all this that has to be done.

125
00:29:04,980 --> 00:29:17,980
 Because this water pipeline is being replaced for us all the time. So we're really excited to get that all done. The only and the other thing I wanted to mention was I appreciate that in your contract.

126
00:29:17,980 --> 00:29:31,980
 You recognize that in order to get housing in Peyonia in this the peak of summer season that you would pay for half of that cost of your housing and utilities.

127
00:29:31,980 --> 00:29:41,980
 And oftentimes the town pays the full cost and we spoke to him yesterday saying, we just don't know what that house has been all up like and that could be more than we really could handle.

128
00:29:41,980 --> 00:29:54,980
 So thank you very much for offering to take half of that. And if the board chooses to go further with your contract. That's the first thing we'll start on is finding a place for you to live.

129
00:29:54,980 --> 00:30:12,980
 Because right now you are available starting June, I think it's Monday, June 15, which is wonderful because we would have a several week overlap with for you to be here while Stefan is here to learn from him and then be able to meet all the staff before Stefan is gone.

130
00:30:12,980 --> 00:30:17,980
 So, thank you for that. So that's all I have and I'll pass it over to Trustee Ostrander.

131
00:30:17,980 --> 00:30:31,980
 Thank you so much for being here and being available. I'm told that you were the only one available. So glad that we had somebody with good experience and small talents. Thanks for your willingness to be present.

132
00:30:31,980 --> 00:30:48,980
 Give a couple of questions if so I went to highlight. Can you talk a little bit about your statement that you believe in promoting citizen involvement in their government and what that means to you and what it looks like from a structural or process perspective.

133
00:30:48,980 --> 00:31:01,980
 I know everyone says they have an open door policy I've heard that more times than I can count but some people say it and don't do it. I very much prefer having people involved in their community.

134
00:31:01,980 --> 00:31:17,980
 And I take active roles in communities in order to break the walls down where people know who I am. And if they have particularly customer based issues, which is what the administrator works with most of the time.

135
00:31:17,980 --> 00:31:24,980
 I look at those as being very different the board deals with what I would call ownership issues.

136
00:31:24,980 --> 00:31:35,980
 And the administrator deals with the customer side of the city. So it's when people come into.

137
00:31:35,980 --> 00:31:49,980
 Town Hall and they have questions about their services things that they need to have accomplished different things like that. That's a role that the staff has to take on and be willing to try to resolve as quickly as possible.

138
00:31:49,980 --> 00:32:10,980
 Because I think it's important to have a level of customer service with the local citizens that resolves their issues and helps them move forward because it can be very frustrating dealing with government and not knowing all the rules and all of the issues that you have to address in order to resolve issues.

139
00:32:10,980 --> 00:32:25,980
 And it's really a good thing for staff and the administrator to break those walls down and make sure that the residents can accomplish their goals and meet their needs.

140
00:32:25,980 --> 00:32:42,980
 Thank you so much. Can you, I know as a city administrator, you have to be very good at playing multiple games at once, or spending multiple place keeping them spending at the same time. Can you talk to us about a situation that you may have had experience?

141
00:32:42,980 --> 00:32:54,980
 You don't have to name names of towns or anything but can you talk about a situation where you had to triage a number of unexpected or burning issues that came up.

142
00:32:54,980 --> 00:33:08,980
 Well, they all tend to stand on their own because of the separation of operations within government. So if, if there's water issues, those tend to stand alone street issues tend to stand alone.

143
00:33:08,980 --> 00:33:30,980
 But there's also times when they cross over each other. One of the things that is not common in Colorado but was common when I was in North Dakota was that all of the water and sewer lines there have to be buried more than seven feet deep just to avoid frost.

144
00:33:30,980 --> 00:33:44,980
 And that makes projects far more expensive because you're digging deeper. Also, we had a road one year where we had a project planned on it where we were going to mill and overlay the road the next year.

145
00:33:44,980 --> 00:34:04,980
 So during the winter, which was a particularly bad winter, the road literally fell apart. And we had to change the project and reconstruct the entire street, rather than just doing a mill and overlay project, and that those kind of things you have to be prepared for because they happen all the time.

146
00:34:04,980 --> 00:34:16,980
 And that's something that you can plan for, whether it does things to city and town infrastructure that you have to be able to work around and resolve.

147
00:34:16,980 --> 00:34:32,980
 And if you get bogged down with the details on those things and can't make decisions, you can't move forward. And I think that's a big key to the administrators role is to be able to see clearly the direction that you need to take.

148
00:34:32,980 --> 00:34:41,980
 Taking advice from engineers and from the board and the staff and making decisions and moving forward with it.

149
00:34:41,980 --> 00:34:48,980
 Going back to the other one I forgot to ask my follow up question we have a couple of citizen committees or we've had them in the past.

150
00:34:48,980 --> 00:35:01,980
 How have you dealt with those types of committees before or have you worked with local governments that have citizen committee committees that come up to deal with special issues.

151
00:35:01,980 --> 00:35:09,980
 Are these standing committees or are these dealing with specific projects.

152
00:35:09,980 --> 00:35:12,980
 Like planning and zoning board.

153
00:35:12,980 --> 00:35:24,980
 No, I'm speaking more about our STR and hot. We had a water committee at one point. We have an STR short term rental committee currently.

154
00:35:24,980 --> 00:35:28,980
 So these are more like ad hoc issues specific.

155
00:35:28,980 --> 00:35:39,980
 Okay. I actually like those kind of committees because you can get people to participate a little more often when they can see an end point to a commitment.

156
00:35:39,980 --> 00:35:55,980
 That's the problem with standing committees is people have to serve for a fairly lengthy period of time and it takes a lot more dedication on people's parts trying to plan how they make that work within the other demands of their life.

157
00:35:55,980 --> 00:36:00,980
 But if it's a short term commitment, it's one that they can see an end of.

158
00:36:00,980 --> 00:36:15,980
 And you can tell them within reasonable within a reasonable timeframe how much how long the project will last and when what they're being asked to do how quickly they're being asked to make decisions and recommendations.

159
00:36:15,980 --> 00:36:25,980
 And when likely they will be able to walk away from that and possibly get involved in a different project in the future.

160
00:36:25,980 --> 00:36:29,980
 But shorter term ad hoc committees.

161
00:36:29,980 --> 00:36:42,980
 I think work especially better in today's world where people are so busy that if they can see a short term commitment, they might be more willing to provide input and participation.

162
00:36:42,980 --> 00:36:54,980
 Thank you so much. A last question I saw in your resume, you talk a little bit about having experience and HR and sort of that, that side of things.

163
00:36:54,980 --> 00:37:02,980
 Can you talk to me a little bit about what that means for you in terms of bringing your HR experience to an administrator's role.

164
00:37:02,980 --> 00:37:13,980
 I've developed HR manuals for two different organizations in my career, and it takes a lot of time. It takes a lot of staff involvement.

165
00:37:13,980 --> 00:37:26,980
 It takes a lot of education with the board to make sure that they know that you're following a lot of laws that can impact a lot of the decisions that are made because it's all employment law.

166
00:37:26,980 --> 00:37:31,980
 It's ways to make decisions and treat staff properly.

167
00:37:31,980 --> 00:37:40,980
 I was involved in starting a local affiliate for what's called the Society for Human Resource Management.

168
00:37:40,980 --> 00:37:44,980
 The acronym for it is SHRM if you've ever heard of that.

169
00:37:44,980 --> 00:37:53,980
 And it was a way to improve communication between myself and human resource directors.

